  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "CWdq5zGq6qvRWm8zF0e6cCagZDI=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\n\n**PSS (Postal Service on Swarm)** delivers anonymous, asynchronous messages by mining a content-addressed chunk (\"Trojan chunk\") whose address lands in the recipient's neighborhood, then push-syncing it through normal chunk traffic.\n\n## Evidence\n\nProtocol:\n1. Sender mines a nonce so the resulting CAC address has a prefix matching the recipient's neighborhood\n2. Message is asymmetrically encrypted with the recipient's public key\n3. The chunk is push-synced via the standard protocol \u2014 indistinguishable from normal encrypted traffic\n4. Recipient's node attempts to decrypt every arriving chunk, checking for a topic match\n\nTrojan chunk layout:\n```\n[8-byte span] [32-byte mined nonce] [4064-byte encrypted payload]\n  Payload: [2-byte msg length] [32-byte obfuscated topic] [message] [random padding]\n```\n\nLatency: seconds (nonce mining scales with network size) + normal forwarding time. If the recipient is offline, the chunk persists until its stamp TTL expires \u2014 delivery is asynchronous.\n\nAPI: `POST /pss/send/{topic}/{targets}?recipient={publicKey}`, `WS /pss/subscribe/{topic}`.\n\n## Why it matters\n\nPSS is the transport for real-time notifications and direct messaging in a fully decentralized Connect. Third parties cannot distinguish PSS traffic from any other encrypted chunk, giving plausible deniability.\n",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z"
    }
  },
